  "prompt": "Does the government have laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the U.S. government has a number of laws against money laundering. Here are some key ones:\n\n*   **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970:** This is the foundation of U.S. anti-money laundering (AML) laws. It requires financial institutions to keep records and file reports on certain financial transactions. This includes reporting suspicious activity that might indicate money laundering, tax evasion, or other criminal activities.\n\n*   **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986:** This law made money laundering a federal crime. It prohibits knowingly engaging in financial transactions with the proceeds of illegal activity.\n\n*   **USA PATRIOT Act of 2001:** Enacted after the 9/11 attacks, this act strengthened AML laws to combat terrorist financing. It expanded the scope of the BSA and increased due diligence requirements for financial institutions.\n\n*   **Money Laundering and Financial Crimes Strategy Act of 1998:** This act requires the development of a national strategy for combating money laundering and other financial crimes.\n\nThese laws (and others) give the government tools to investigate, prosecute, and prevent money laundering. They also impose significant compliance burdens on financial institutions.",
